  "footnotes": [
    "Battle of Avarayr (451 CE): the Armenian nobility under Vard Mamikonian fought the Sassanid Persian army to defend Christianity; though militarily a defeat, it became the founding myth of Armenian national identity — resistance to forced conversion; the Sassanids eventually granted Armenia religious autonomy (Treaty of Nvarsak, 484)",
    "Kingdom of Georgia's Golden Age (1008–1220): under King David IV 'the Builder' and Queen Tamar, Georgia became the dominant Caucasian power controlling much of the southern Caucasus, northeastern Anatolia, and parts of northern Persia; Rustaveli composed The Knight in the Panther's Skin at Tamar's court",
    "Fall of Ani (1064): the Seljuk Turk conquest of the Armenian capital Ani (described by contemporaries as one of the great cities of the medieval world, with a population claimed at 100,000) effectively ended Armenian political independence for nearly nine centuries",
    "Armenian Genocide (1915–1923): Ottoman authorities systematically deported and massacred the Armenian population of Anatolia; estimates of deaths range from 600,000 to 1.5 million; the event is recognized as genocide by most historians and numerous states, though Turkey disputes this characterization",
    "Baku oil boom (1870s–1900s): after Russian annexation, Baku became one of the world's first oil cities; by 1900 it produced roughly half the world's oil; Nobel and Rothschild family fortunes were built here; the industry's wealth financed much of early Azerbaijani national consciousness"
  ]
